posts.name: Beck's Cajun Cafe
posts.note: Beck's Cajun Cafe is a bustling counter serve dishing up Cajun and Creole comfort food to the farmers market crowd. You need to make sure order a train wreck which contains Andouille sausage, steak, salami, and onions served on a french baguette with cheese and creole mayo. It's one of my favorite sandwiches in the country. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Beiler's Bakery
posts.note: Beiler's Bakery is the destination in Reading Terminal Market for baked goods, including Pennsylvania Dutch classics and a variety of housemade donuts. The blueberry or apple fritter is a must have. They are in my top three favorite fritters in the country. Any other donut you choose won't be a bad thing here. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Bing Bing Dim Sum
posts.note: Bing Bing Dim Sum serves Chinese plates with a Jewish twist, and festive scorpion bowls are served at this snug, energetic spot. Their food is often informed by tradition, but it’s never defined by it. All that they require of your willing mind and a willing stomach. The owners of Bing Bing Dim Sum also own CheU Noodle Bar, Nunu, and CheU Fishtown.

posts.name: CheU Fishtown
posts.note: CheU Fishtown is hip ramen bar with graffitied walls serves noodles and Asian bites, plus beer, wine, and cocktails. Their food is often informed by tradition, but it’s never defined by it. All that they require of your willing mind and a willing stomach. The owners of CheU Fishtown also own CHeU Noodle Bar, Bing Bing Dim Sum, and Nunu.

posts.name: Dalessandro's Steaks
posts.note: Dalessandro's Steaks is a cheesesteak counter that caters to a local crowd with steaks, hoagies, burgers, and salads. For more than half a century later, they have kept their customers grinning from ear to ear.

posts.name: Di Bruno Brothers
posts.note: Di Bruno Brothers is an acclaimed gourmet destination supplying meats, cheeses, and prepared foods, plus specialty items. When you visit, you won't go home hungry since whenever you ask about a product, they will give you some to taste. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Federal Donuts
posts.note: Federal Donuts has buzzy counter serve dishing Korean-style fried chicken, creative donuts & coffee till they run out. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Han Dynasty - Old City
posts.note: Han Dynasty - Old City serves Sichuan eats, along with a late-night street-food menu (Thursday, Friday, and Saturday) served in grand digs with high ceilings. NOTE: They have multiple locations.
posts.rcmmnd: Best Chinese restaurant in every state from MSN website

posts.name: Isgro's Bakery
posts.note: Isgro's Bakery is the venerable bake shop turning out cannoli, cakes, cookies, custards, tarts and other Italian pastries. I go there for their cannoli's, but all their pastries look delicious.

posts.name: Nunu
posts.note: Nunu cooks what they like to eat — it’s personal, no matter what they put in front of you. Their food is often informed by tradition, but it’s never defined by it. All that they require of your willing mind and a willing stomach. The owners of Nunu also own CHeU Noodle Bar, Bing Bing Dim Sum, and CHeU Fishtown. Alex Hillman recommends the 'Pork Katsu' sandwich and the impossible burger. From the Philadelphia Eater website, 'Shawn Darragh and Ben Puchowitz of Cheu and Bing Bing Dim Sum are just about ready to debut Nunu, their small, stylish, very red Japanese bar next door to Cheu Fishtown.'

posts.name: Murph's Bar
posts.note: At Murph's Bar, pennies cover the bar in this comfy Irish pub with an exposed-brick interior and quirky decorations. I read on Alex Hillman's Twitter that 'Murph's on Girard has some of the best Italian food in the city of Philadelphia.' From Bon Appetit magazine's website, 'It’s an Italian red sauce joint inside of an Irish pub. There’s only one guy that works in the kitchen. He cooks everything. He’s from Italy. It’s always slammed. There are hardly any seats. You have to go early on a weeknight if you want to get in without waiting for like...two hours. It’s affordable. There’s a weird, vague Elvis theme.'

posts.name: Reading Terminal Market
posts.note: Reading Terminal Market is a famous indoor farmer's market offering diverse fare, housewares and area specialties since 1892. There is so much to do and eat while you're here make sure to go hungry.

posts.name: Revolution Taco
posts.note: Revolution Taco is a casual, counter-serve taqueria featuring unique fillings, including meat, fish, and veggie options. From their website, 'Revolution Taco is the concept of Chef Carolyn Nguyen. With her classically trained chef approach, Carolyn uses the taco shell as a vehicle to create global-inspired dishes as tacos. Some menu highlights include: Korean Beef tacos, Roasted Duck tacos served on a scallion pancake, and our vegan BBQ Cauliflower tacos.'

posts.name: Sarvida
posts.note: From the Philly Magazine website, 'Sarvida is a modern take on classic Filipino cuisine. Traditional ingredients and spices, but presented with the fine-tuned finesse of a professional chef. While Perla offers both ends of the Filipino food spectrum — upscale, modern, a la carte Thursdays through Saturdays; family-style, eat-with-your-hands Kamayan dinners on Wednesdays and Sundays — Sarvida will live somewhere in the middle — an all a la carte menu with small and large plates (whole fish and chicken dishes) designed to share.'

posts.name: Silk City
posts.note: Silk City is a renovated diner with an outdoor beer garden serves classics like fried chicken and meatloaf. You should order one or all of these: the duck confit egg roll or the pork and crab pot stickers or meatloaf.

posts.name: South Philly Barbacoa
posts.note: South Philly Barbacoa serves unassuming Mexican eatery specializing in traditional slow-cooked barbacoa-style tacos and toppings. You need to get the pork and the lamb tacos.

posts.name: Standard Tap
posts.note: Standard Tap is a multilevel spot featuring a rotating menu of American eats and a variety of local beers on tap.

posts.name: Summit Diner
posts.note: The Summit Diner is a retro diner with a vintage vibe dishing up comfort food favorites such as burgers and fries. You need to try their breakfasts which are huge. Their cheese, mushroom, and green pepper omelette, with hash browns, wheat toast, along with a side of scrapple is filling and then some.
posts.cptn: Cheese, mushroom, green pepper omelette, with hash browns, wheat toast, scrapple for $10.04 in Somerset, PA, at the Summit Diner.

posts.name: Tommy Di Nic's
posts.note: Tommy Di Nic's crowds pack this venerable Reading Terminal Market sandwich counter celebrated for its roast pork and make sure to get sharp provolone on your sandwich. Their roast pork with aged provolone is world famous, and the meatball or the roast beef subs aren't bad either.

posts.name: Umai Umai
posts.note: Umai Umai is n inventive sushi, specialty rolls, and hot entrees are offered in contemporary, intimate surroundings.

posts.name: V Street
posts.note: V Street serves vegan riffs on global street food served in small wood-and-brick space with a bar and kitchen counter. From their website 'V Street offers a fun and exciting approach to vegetable cooking inspired by street food culture from all over the world. Located in a little 'jewel box' space just off Rittenhouse Square.'

posts.name: Vedge
posts.note: Vedge is a restaurant serving inventive vegan and vegetarian small plates in a charming old mansion. From the Philadelphia Eater website, 'Rich Landau and Kate Jacoby reinvented meatless dining in Philly by making vegetables — not meat substitutes — the star at Vedge, an elegant eatery set in a former mansion. Through culinary skill and maybe a little magic, mushrooms become ribbons of pasta and radishes impersonate sushi.' Also, more from the Vedge website, 'A Vegetable Restaurant by James Beard-nominated Chefs Rich Landau and Kate Jacoby; Vedge offers an exciting dining experience inspired by seasonal vegetables since 2011. Housed in the historic Tiger Building in Center City Philadelphia, the elegant brownstone home is an intimate setting for inventive vegetable cooking. The Bar features natural wines, plenty of craft beers, and a creative cocktail list, all selected to complement the wide range of tastes through the dinner and dessert menus. Vedge serves dinner seven nights a week and is available for private parties of various sizes.'
